The '''Rabindra Parishad''' is a multi-purpose cultural centre on [[Beer Chand Patel Path]] in [[Patna]], India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110510/jsp/bihar/story_13959249.jsp |title=The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) &#124; Bihar &#124; Morning march to pay tribute to Tagore |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-05-10 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref>

==Overview==
Named after [[Rabindranath Tagore]], it was established in 1948.<ref name="indiatimes1">{{cite web|author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Rabindra-Bhawan-gets-a-new-auditorium/articleshow/7438263.cms?referral=PM |title=Rabindra Bhawan gets a new auditorium - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2011-02-06 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> The building contains a musical school (known as Geet Bhawan),<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Acclaimed-artists-to-perform-in-Patna/articleshow/25398026.cms |title=Acclaimed artists to perform in Patna - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-11-08 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> a library with books on and by Tagore,<ref name="official">{{cite web | url=http://rabindraparishadpatna.org/aboutus.htm | title=RABINDRA PARISHAD :: Patna - Bihar - India | publisher=Rabindraparishadpatna.org | accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> and an auditorium, known as Rabindra Bhavan, which is an important theater in Patna where cultural and theatrical activities takes place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120507/jsp/bihar/story_15458447.jsp#.U11j0YGDkTA |title=Chandalika finale to Tagore festivity |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2012-05-07 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> The programme of performances ranges from theatre, to live music, comedy, dance, visual art, spoken word and children's events.

During 2008 to 2010, the theater went a major renovation and suspension. The overall renovation cost was estimated about {{INR}}1.5 crore. After renovation, the auditorium's seating capacity was increased from 655<ref name="official" /> to 1,000 and the theater’s structure were improved, too. In February 2011, the state-of-the-art auditorium was inaugurated by the Chief Minister of Bihar, [[Nitish Kumar]].<ref name="indiatimes1"/>

